[1] Dominican Republic
Date: Wed 16 May 2007
Source: Terra, Espana [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://actualidad.terra.es/sociedad/articulo/rdominicana_registra_casos_dengue_mayo_1577787.htm>
The Minister of Health of the Dominican Republic, Juan Bautista
Rojas, said today [16 May 2007], that 1900 dengue cases had been
registered in the country from the beginning of this year [2007],
until 15 May [2007], and that, according to government estimates,
this number could rise to 6500 by the end of the year.
So far this year [2007], 4 people have died from dengue and health
authorities are studying 4 other cases who possible died of this
disease, added the Minister.
Of the 1900 registered cases during these months [in 2007], 56 have
been DHF, the most serious disease, and the rest have been classical
dengue [fever].
In all of 2006, there were 6252 cases of DHF, with 53 deaths, and
6061 cases of classical dengue [fever].
The majority of these reported cases in the Dominican Republic have
been recorded in the areas of greatest population, such as the
provinces of Santo Domingo, Distrito Nacional, Santiago (north), and
Peravia (south).
Over the past month, the Ministry of Public Health has carried out a
campaign to fight dengue, in which 3 million students have
participated and [more than 1.2 million] homes have been visited. In
addition, 2.7 million booklets with advice on the proper storage of
domestic water have been distributed among students and teachers.
These water containers are potential breeding sites for _Aedes
aegypti_, the vector that transmits the virus.
This campaign has permitted the elimination of [more than one
million] mosquito breeding sites, according to the Minister, who is
confident that his department has contributed to the "generation of
the desired awareness" within the population.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The total number of cases reported in 2006, which provides a greater
number of DHF cases (6252) than of classical dengue [fever] (6061)
is, by all measures, inexact. The proportion of classical [dengue
fever] cases to DHF cases is always at least 10-15:1 and it is easier
to recognize the latter than the former. Therefore, the real number
of dengue cases that are not DHF must always be an order of magnitude
greater than the number of complicated [DHF] cases.
The official numbers reflect a clear underreporting of the classical
form or an exaggerated overestimation of DHF [cases]. - Mod.JT; [in
Spanish, trans. Mod.TY]
[A map of the Dominican Republic can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/dominican_republic_pol_04.jpg>
