[3] American Samoa
Date: Thu 17 May 2007
Source: Radio New Zealand International [edited]
<http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=32324>

The Department of Health in American Samoa is stressing the
importance of the '3 D's' of dengue prevention.
There have been 16 reported cases of dengue fever in American Samoa
this year [2007], an increase of 9 cases since last month [April 2007].
The Public Health Officer and Medical Director for the Department of
Health, Dr Ivan Tuliau, says there are 3 key steps to help prevent
dengue fever. "We're calling it the '3 D's' of dengue prevention: the
1st is drain, 'D' for drain standing water around the house that may
serve as mosquito breeding sites. The 2nd 'D' is for dress
protective, long sleeve shirts, long pants, covering exposed skin as
possible; and the last, is to use mosquito repellant containing DEET."
Dr Tuliau says the last dengue epidemic [in the country] was in 2001,
when there were more than 100 cases of dengue fever, but from 2003 to
2006, only 3 dengue cases were reported.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks
[It would be interesting to know which of the _Aedes_ mosquito
vectors is transmitting the virus during this outbreak, and which
dengue virus type is involved.
A map of American Samoa can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/cia07/american_samoa_sm_2007.gif>. - Mod.TY]
